//why   long long x = x0 + k * (B / g); ,long long y = y0 - k * (A / g); 
//the core conceptual question behind the Extended Euclidean Algorithmâ€™s general solution:

Why are all integer solutions to
Ax+By=gcd(A,B)
of the form:
  ğ‘¥=ğ‘¥0+kâ‹…ğµ/ğ·,ğ‘¦=ğ‘¦0-k.ğ´/ğ·
where D=gcd(A,B) and
(ğ‘¥0,ğ‘¦0) is one particular solution?

Letâ€™s break it down.
âœ… 1. What does the Extended Euclidean Algorithm do?
It finds one particular solution (ğ‘¥0,ğ‘¦0),to:
            ğ´ğ‘¥0+ğµğ‘¦0=ğ·=gcd(ğ´,ğµ)
This means we now know one valid integer solution.
But there are infinitely many integer pairs (x,y) that satisfy this equation.

âœ… 2. What happens if we add another solution?
Letâ€™s suppose thereâ€™s another solution (x,y) such that:
                Ax+By=D
We want to know:
How is this new pair (x,y) related to the original (ğ‘¥0,ğ‘¦0)?

Subtract the two equations:

Ax+By=D ------eq(1)
âˆ’(Ax0+By0=D) ------eq(2)
Subtracting:
        A(xâˆ’x0)+B(yâˆ’y0)=0
This means:
        A(xâˆ’x0)=âˆ’B(yâˆ’y0)
So:
        ğ´(ğ‘¥âˆ’ğ‘¥0)+ğµ(ğ‘¦âˆ’ğ‘¦0)=0â‡’ğ´(ğ‘¥âˆ’ğ‘¥0)=âˆ’ğµ(ğ‘¦âˆ’ğ‘¦0)

This is the homogeneous equation (right-hand side is 0), and its solutions describe the "shifts"
from the original solution that still satisfy the equation.

âœ… 3. Solving the homogeneous part
From: A(xâˆ’x0)=âˆ’B(yâˆ’y0) ----eq(3)
  We want integer solutions.
Let:
  ğ‘¥âˆ’ğ‘¥0 = ğ‘˜â‹…ğµ/ğ·, ğ‘¦âˆ’ğ‘¦0 = âˆ’ğ‘˜â‹…ğ´/ğ· 
Then:
    x=x0+kâ‹… D/B
    y=y0âˆ’kâ‹… D/A
And this will always satisfy:
    Ax+By=D

âœ… 4. Why divide by D?
Because if:
    D=gcd(A,B)
Then both 
ğ´/ğ·  and ğµ/ğ· are integers, and this is the smallest unit of change you can use to stay within the solution space.

Any larger step would skip some valid integer solutions.

ğŸ”š Summary
| Concept                         | Why itâ€™s true                                                  |
| ------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------- |
| A x + B y = D                   | We get one solution (x0, y0)                                   |
| All other solutions             | Come from shifting  B/D, A/D                                   |
| x = x0 + k.{B}/{D}              | Adding multiples of B/D to stay on the solution line           |
| y = y0 - k.{A}/{D}              | Subtracting matching shifts in y                               |
| Why k âˆˆ â„¤                       | Because we want all integer solutions                          |


